## Introduction

Growth in a living system is defined as the increase in some quantity over time (e.g. Von Bertalanffy 1934, Lugert et al. 2016). Growth depends on biotic (e.g. density, sex, age, genetics) and abiotic (e.g. water chemistry, temperature, photoperiod, and oxygen levels) factors. Achieving an optimal body size is crucial for reproductive fitness, physiology, and ecological interactions, ultimately driving the survival of the species (Solokas et al). This analysis sought to delineate which parameters primarily affected growth in YYmale EBT after their introduction in the wild between the years 2018-2022. We examined the changes in growth of YY EBT males during the time between their first release in the wild and at recapture after one year, examining the associations with possible interfering factors such as size, condition, site, group, timing, or environmental temperature at release or their propensity to move, in order to define the most important variables contributing to (or inhibiting) their growth during the first year in the wild. We examined how growth rate, calculated dividing observed body size parameters across time, could be affected by differences in grouping or timing of release, and whether size (forklenght) at first release would have a significant effect on the growth of introduced YY EBT males. We also included in the analysis the condition factor K, 
$$
k = \frac{\text{weight} \times 10^5}{\text{length}^3}
$$
an index of the relative degree of plumpness of the fish (Tyus, 2012) and the extent of distance moved for each fish with the assumption that movement propensity would signal better acclimation (what do you think about this one?). 

