## Possible themes for discussion
These analyses showed that higher summer temperatures, larger size at release, and higher-distances-moved significantly contributed to slower or no growth in one year yy male EBT introduced in the Pend Oreille tributaries. Differences occur also depending on the year of release cohort possibly because of the fish size at release (Fig. 2) and timing of release (august vs october). 
Condition at release did not cause any significant changes in growth rate (Fig 3.). 
What could the implications of these results mean? Fish grow at different rates throughout their life time. Introducing larger fish into the system may have allowed the ones that have already attained larger sizes before their introduction to allocate less effort to growth and to move more (Fig 4). In fact, negative growth is more likely to be observed for fish that move more (t-test, p<0.001) as well as for those with larger sizes at release (t-test, p<0.001). Regarding temperature, higher temperatures have, in general, been shown to negatively influence bodysize in fish, particularly in cold water systems  (Rypel 2014, Bergmann's rule). Therefore, differential temperature at sites of release could have an effect on YY males post-release growth, although this needs to be investigated in more detail. 

